To create a Discord bot with Discord.js v14 that has one slash command to ban a member, follow these steps:

1. First, make sure you have the necessary dependencies installed. If you haven't already installed the dependencies, run the following command in your project directory:

```
npm install discord.js @discordjs/builders @discordjs/rest
```

2. Create a new file (e.g., `index.js`) and add the following code to set up the bot and define the ban command:

```javascript
const { Client, Collection, Intents } = require('discord.js');
const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v9');

// Replace 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN' with your actual bot token
const TOKEN = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';
const GUILD_ID = 'YOUR_GUILD_ID';

// Replace 'BAN_COMMAND_NAME' with the name you want for your ban command
const COMMAND_NAME = 'ban';
const COMMAND_DESCRIPTION = 'Bans a member from the server';

// Create a new Discord client
const client = new Client({
    intents: [Intents.FLAGS.GUILDS, Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MEMBERS, Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_BANS, Intents.FLAGS.GUILD_MESSAGES]
});

// Register the ban command
const commands = [
    {
        name: COMMAND_NAME,
        description: COMMAND_DESCRIPTION
    }
];

// Create a new REST instance with the client ID, guild ID, and token
const rest = new REST({ version: '9' }).setToken(TOKEN);

// Register the ban command with the guild
(async () => {
    try {
        await rest.put(
            Routes.applicationGuildCommands(GUILD_ID, client.user.id),
            { body: commands }
        );

        console.log('Successfully registered application commands.');
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Error registering application commands', error);
    }
})();

// Handle the ban command
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

    const { commandName } = interaction;

    if (commandName === COMMAND_NAME) {
        if (interaction.user.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
            try {
                await interaction.guild.members.ban(interaction.options.getUser('user'));
                await interaction.reply('Successfully banned the user.');
            } catch (error) {
                console.error('Error banning user', error);
                await interaction.reply('An error occurred while trying to ban the user.');
            }
        } else {
            await interaction.reply('You do not have permission to use this command.');
        }
    }
});

// Login to Discord with the token
client.login(TOKEN);
```

3. Replace `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN'` with your actual bot token. You can find your bot token in the Discord Developer Portal when you create your bot.

4. Replace `'YOUR_GUILD_ID'` with the ID of the guild you want to register the ban command in. You can find the guild ID in the Discord Developer Portal under the "OAuth2" tab.

5. Replace `'BAN_COMMAND_NAME'` with the name you want your ban command to have. You can change this to anything you like, but make sure it is unique and matches the name you use in the command.

6. Run the bot by executing the JavaScript file (e.g., `index.js`) using Node.js:

```
node index.js
```

7. Once the bot is running, you can use the ban command in your guild by typing `/ban @user`, replacing `@user` with the mention of the user you want to ban.

Now you have a Discord bot with Discord.js v14 that has one slash command to ban a member.

Creating a function that converts Markdown to HTML involves handling various Markdown syntax like headings, lists, bold and italic text, links, etc. Below is a basic implementation of such a function in C++. Note that this is a simplified version and might not cover all edge cases or more complex Markdown features.

To use this function, you would need to include the necessary headers and have a way to handle memory management (e.g., using `std::vector` for dynamically allocated strings).

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>
#include <vector>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::istringstream markdownStream(markdown);
    std::string line;
    bool inCodeBlock = false;
    std::vector<char> buffer;

    while (std::getline(markdownStream, line)) {
        for (char c : line) {
            if (inCodeBlock) {
                if (c == '\n') {
                    if (buffer.size() > 0 && buffer.back() == '`') {
                        buffer.pop_back();
                    }
                } else if (c == '`') {
                    buffer.push_back(c);
                }
            } else {
                if (c == '[') {
                    int pos = line.find(']');
                    if (pos != std::string::npos) {
                        std::string linkText = line.substr(1, pos - 1);
                        std::string linkHref = line.substr(pos + 1);
                        html += "<a href=\"" + linkHref + "\">" + linkText + "</a>";
                        line = line.substr(pos + linkHref.length() + 1);
                    }
                } else if (c == '_') {
                    if (line.find('_') != std::string::npos) {
                        std::string boldText = line.substr(1, line.find('_') - 1);
                        html += "<b>" + boldText + "</b>";
                        line = line.substr(line.find('_') + 1);
                    }
                } else if (c == '#') {
                    int pos = line.find(' ');
                    if (pos != std::string::npos) {
                        std::string headingText = line.substr(1, pos - 1);
                        html += "<h" + std::to_string(pos + 1) + ">" + headingText + "</h" + std::to_string(pos + 1) + ">";
                        line = line.substr(pos + 1);
                    }
                } else if (c == '*') {
                    if (line.find('*') != std::string::npos) {
                        std::string italicText = line.substr(1, line.find('*') - 1);
                        html += "<i>" + italicText + "</i>";
                        line = line.substr(line.find('*') + 1);
                    }
                } else {
                    html += c;
                }
            }
        }
        if (!inCodeBlock) {
            html += "<br>";
        }
        inCodeBlock = false;
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = "This is a *bold* text and an _italic_ text.\n\n"
                                "### This is a heading\n"
                                "Some text\n\n"
                                "This is a [link](http://example.com)\n\n"
                                "```cpp\nstd::cout << \"Hello, World!\" << std::endl;\n```\n";
    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This function handles:
1. **Bold and Italic Text**: Uses `_` for italic and `*` for bold.
2. **Headings**: Converts `#` to `<h1>`, `##` to `<h2>`, etc.
3. **Links**: Converts `[text](url)` to `<a href="url">text</a>`.
4. **Code Blocks**: Uses triple backticks `` ` `` to wrap code blocks.

You can extend this function to handle additional Markdown features like lists, images, and more advanced syntax as needed.

